One example of Baron Evola's maxim that biological seniority and spiritual seniority not always overlap is how when St. Iakovos was a small boy the wife of his village's priest was struggling when giving birth and the priest sent people to call St. Iakovos and begged him to help.

It's almost a comical image and very endearing, the terrified village priest worried his wife will die in labor pain and asking a little child to save her, because he knew St. Iakovos was already a spiritual giant even in childhood. His prayers worked of course and all was well.

Fun fact, but apparently St. Gabriel Urgebadze (same one who burned down the giant Lenin banner during the communist parade in Georgia) really loved opera. Liked to go to the opera whenever he could. Wonderful that saints also get to have regular guy hobbies on the side.
St. John of Shanghai

Seeing it this way, him lighting the Lenin image on fire in front of the entire city staring in horror is itself a very grandiose, theatrical gesture. It must have had a striking effect on the people seeing it. Other saints would be content just standing on the street preaching.

A river is the best place to repent in. St. Wandregesilius fought lust so he prayed the psalter in a river at wintertime, prostrating himself into the cold water at each psalm. Adam and Eve stood in the Jordan and Tigris for 40 and 37 days with the water to their necks to repent.

If you're one of those Americans with a literal river running through your backyard you can just sit there when it's cold and recite psalms until you almost freeze. They also have waterproof Bibles now. Apparently they first came out in 2005. Powerful novel spiritual technology.
